"{\n  \"correct\": \"no\",\n  \"explanation\": \"The issue with this code is that after closing the figure with `plt.close()` on line 11, it tries to access the axis object `ax` which belongs to the closed figure on line 18. This will result in an error because the figure is already closed.\",\n  \"patch\": \"18c18\\n<ax.text(0.4, 0.4, \\\"Add a label to the current active figure\\\")\\n---\\n>ac_fig.text(0.4, 0.4, \\\"Add a label to the current active figure\\\") doesn't work here because we can't use text method directly on figure object, we should use axis instead.\\n So we should get the axis of the active figure first then add text to it.\\n18c18,19\\n<ax.text(0.4, 0.4, \\\"Add a label to the current active figure\\\")\\n<plt.show(block=False)\\n---\\n>ac_fig_ax = ac_fig.get_axes()[0]\\n>ac_fig_ax.text(0.4, 0.4, \\\"Add a label to the current active figure\\\")\\n But still this will fail because we are trying to show a figure after it has been closed.\\n So the correct patch should be to move the plt.close() after we show the plot.\\n11d10\\n<plt.close()\\n---\\n\\n20d18\\n<plt.close()\\n---\\n\\n11a12\\n>plt.show(block=False)\\n>plt.close()\\n So the corrected code is:\\n1  import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\\n2  \\n3  def get_active_figure():\\n4      fig_stack = plt.get_fignums()\\n5      if len(fig_stack) == 0:\\n6          return None\\n7      return plt.gcf()\\n8  \\n9  fig, ax = plt.subplots()\\n10 ax.plot([0, 1, 2, 3], [0, 4, 5, 6])\\n11 plt.show(block=False)\\n12 plt.close()\\n13 \\n14 ac_fig = get_active_figure()\\n15 \\n16 if ac_fig is None:\\n17     print(\\\"No active figure\\\")\\n18 else:\\n19     fig2, ax2 = plt.subplots()\\n20     ax2.text(0.4, 0.4, \\\"Add a label to the current active figure\\\")\\n21     plt.show(block=False)\\n22     plt.close()\"\n}"